The '''2008 Africa Cup of Nations''', also known as the '''MTN Africa Cup of Nations''' due to the competition's sponsorship by [[MTN Group|MTN]], was the 26th edition of the [[Africa Cup of Nations]], the biennial [[association football|football]] tournament for nations affiliated to the [[Confederation of African Football]] (CAF). The tournament was staged at four venues around Ghana between 20 January and 10 February 2008. 

[[Egypt national football team|Egypt]] won the tournament, beating [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] 1–0 in the final. As winners, they qualified for the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]] as African representatives. With 99 goals, it was the highest-scoring [[Africa Cup of Nations]] ever.

==Host selection==
'''Bids:'''
* {{Flag|Ghana}}
* {{flag|Libya|1977}}
* {{Flag|South Africa}}

The organization of the 2008 [[Africa Cup of Nations]] was awarded to [[Ghana]] on 8 July 2004 by the [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]] Executive Committee members which are 12 in [[Cairo]], [[Egypt]]. Voters had a choice between [[Ghana]] and [[Libya]] which was disadvantaged by the fact that two countries in the North Africa region had already hosted the last two editions ([[Tunisia]] in [[2004 African Cup of Nations|2004]], and [[Egypt]] in [[2006 African Cup of Nations|2006]]).

South Africa, also was a candidate at the start, eventually withdrew in May 2004 after being nominated for the organization of the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].

This is the fourth time that Ghana has hosted the African Cup after [[1963 African Cup of Nations|1963]], [[1978 African Cup of Nations|1978]] and [[2000 African Cup of Nations|2000]] (jointly with [[Nigeria]]).
